	<BODY>
		<DIV CLASS="nvis offs">
			.\"
			<BR>
			.Dd <SPAN CLASS="nvis">$Mdocdate$</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.Dt <SPAN CLASS="nvis">MANUALS 7</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.Os
			<BR>
			.Sh <SPAN CLASS="h1">NAME</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.\"
			<BR>
			.Nm <SPAN>UNIX Manual Pages</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.Nd <SPAN>structure, style, and composition</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.\"
			<BR>
			.Sh <SPAN CLASS="h1">DESCRIPTION</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.\"
			<BR>
			.Em <SPAN CLASS="em">A utility without good documentation is of no utility at all.</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.Pp
			<DIV>
			So you've written a utility, library, or driver (or started writing one), and you want to document your work.
			<BR>
			How do you get from code to
			</DIV>
			.Xr <SPAN>man</SPAN> 1
			<DIV>
			output?
			</DIV>
			.Pp
			<DIV>
			This site is a resource for composing well-formed and maintainable UNIX manuals (<Q>manpages</Q>) in
			</DIV>
			.Xr <A CLASS="man external" HREF="http://mdocml.bsd.lv/mdoc.7.html">mdoc</A> 7 <SPAN CLASS="offs">,</SPAN>
			<DIV>
			a language designed specifically for manpages and available by default on most reasonable UNIX installations.
			</DIV>
			.\"
			<BR>
			.Sh <SPAN CLASS="h2">Templates</SPAN>
			<BR>
			.\"
			<TABLE>
				<COL CLASS="left">
				<COL>
				<TBODY>
					<TR>
						<TD>.Lk <A HREF="template.1">template.1</A></TD>
						<TD><SPAN CLASS="offs">Template for a utility manual</SPAN></TD>
					</TR>
					<TR>
						<TD>.Lk <A HREF="template.3">template.3</A></TD>
						<TD><SPAN CLASS="offs">Template for a library/function manual</SPAN></TD>
					</TR>
				</TBODY>
			</TABLE>
			.\"
			<BR>
